To modify your existing code snippet so that it ignores the "Shift+Enter" combination and only triggers the `sendMessage()` function when "Enter" alone is pressed, you can add a condition to check if the `shiftKey` property of the event object (`e`) is `false`. Here's how you can update the code:

```javascript
document.addEventListener("keypress", (e) => {
    if (e.key === "Enter" && !e.shiftKey) { // Check if Enter is pressed without the Shift key
        if (document.getElementById("user-input").value !== "") {
            sendMessage();
        }
    }
});
```

In this updated code:
- `e.shiftKey` will be `true` if the Shift key is held down when the keypress event was fired.
- Using `!e.shiftKey` ensures that `sendMessage()` is only called when "Enter" is pressed without the Shift key. 

This way, "Shift+Enter" won’t trigger `sendMessage()`, accommodating any scenario where you might want to use "Shift+Enter" for a different functionality, like inserting a newline in a textarea or input field.
